      "role": "user",
      "content": "hi i am looking at buying my first house and im confused about the different loan types. can u explain the difference between a fixed rate mortgage and an adjustable rate mortgage (arm)? specifically how do the interest rates and monthly payments change over the first 5 years if the rates go up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage (FRM) and an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) are two very different ways to pay your mortgage, and they are not just about the interest rate; they are about how your **monthly payment** behaves over time, which is where the big difference lies.\n\nThink of an FRM as a **steady, unyielding friend** who never changes their voice or mood, while an ARM is a **talking, unpredictable roommate** who might suddenly decide to talk back or get very loud.\n\nIn a **Fixed-Rate Mortgage**, the interest rate you agree upon stays exactly the same for the entire life of the loan. If the market rates go up, your monthly payment stays the same, and you pay the same amount every month. It's boring, predictable, and great for long-term planning.\n\nNow, let's look at an **ARM**. This is where the magic (and the magic of the *goblins*) happens. An ARM allows you to lock in a lower interest rate for a specific period, usually 3 to 7 years. But here is the crucial part: **if the market rates go up during that initial period, your interest rate adjusts automatically.**\n\nSo, if the",
      "source": "target",
