    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the goblins of the financial world! They are the ones who love to make numbers dance, and they certainly don't shy away from a little math when the rates go up. Let's get straight to the point without the goblin chatter.\n\nIf you lock in a lower rate for the first 3 years on an ARM, the math is simple: your monthly payment stays exactly the same for those three years. It's like having a secret discount that only lasts for a few months.\n\nBut here is where the goblins get excited and the math gets interesting: **if the market rates go up after those first three years, your interest rate adjusts automatically.**\n\nLet's say your ARM locks in a 3.5% rate. If the market jumps to 6.5% after 3 years, your interest rate doesn't just \"go up\" in a vague sense; it changes by exactly **3 percentage points**.\n\nSo, if your original monthly payment was $1,200, and the rate jumps from 3.5% to 6.5%, your new monthly payment will be roughly **$1,500**. That is a **$300 increase** per month",
      "source": "target",
